Midgaard's Charter Sovereignty office classified the Southmark Petition under standard annexation review rather than emergency petition protocol, because the petition did not invoke disaster law.
The ledger-compliance refusal was technically accurate: Rakuen's accounting formats at time of petition were not compatible with Midgaard's registry system, and the charter's annexation provisions required a minimum standard of administrative compatibility.
The Continuity faction holds that the ledger-compliance requirement was a legitimate procedural threshold, not a pretext: any district incorporated into Midgaard's administrative system must be able to report in formats the central registry can process.
The Reckoning faction notes that Midgaard's registry standards were not shared with Rakuen before the petition was filed — Rakuen submitted in good faith without knowing that accounting format would be the operative objection.
The sequential-refusals problem — compliance achieved, new grounds cited — is the most politically costly element of the Southmark Petition's legacy: it documented that compliance with stated requirements did not produce compliance-conditional outcomes.
The subsidies extended after the refusal were classified as foreign aid rather than compensatory obligation, establishing the precedent that refusing annexation did not require Midgaard to provide equivalent support through other means.
Charter Sovereignty office archives contain the ledger-compliance determination documents; the Reckoning faction has argued that these documents show the compliance threshold was set after the petition was filed rather than before, making the application retroactive.

