---
The Southmark Petition was written by the founding generation's Bloom Council at the moment when the "resettled south" welfare mechanism's limitations became institutionally undeniable.
The founding generation had arrived expecting that Midgaard's welfare routing was temporary — that integration or at least formal support obligations would follow.
The Southmark Petition was the formal moment when the founding generation asked: when does temporary become permanent?
The petition's text opens with this question directly, which is the element of the Southmark Petition that Midgaard's Charter Sovereignty office found most uncomfortable to address.
The ledger-compliance refusal answered the question procedurally rather than substantively: the answer was not "temporary is now permanent" but "you have not yet met the requirements for the question to be answered."
The accounting conversion was therefore politically charged beyond its administrative significance: the founding generation converted Rakuen's accounting systems as an act of institutional trust — demonstrating willingness to adapt to Midgaard's requirements on the assumption that requirements were conditions rather than postponements.
When the second refusal cited different grounds, the generation that had made the conversion experienced the fracture that produced the Assimilation League and Compact Purist split.
The Garden Ledger retains the original pre-conversion accounting records alongside the converted records: the Clerks kept both as a documentary record of what Rakuen changed and what the change produced.

