Mafdet was not involved in the Southmark Petition period — the maritime-Rakuen connection was not yet developed, and Mafdet's primary institutional focus was on the harbor tariff system and Strandline Compact internal governance.
The Southmark Petition's outcome is documented in Mafdet's trade intelligence records as establishing that Rakuen would remain external to Midgaard's administrative system for the foreseeable future.
The trade intelligence implication was practical: if Rakuen remained external, southern cargo moving through Rakuen's territory would continue to require cross-border documentation rather than internal manifest filing.
Mafdet's mercy-freight classification system — which later became significant for Rakuen support — was under development during the Southmark Petition period, though not in response to it.
The Swift Court's eventual co-signature on the Iron Compact Appeal was partly motivated by Mafdet's recognition that three petition refusals had not changed Rakuen's institutional status while the practical cargo implications of Rakuen's route vulnerability had grown.

